	   <tr><td colspan=2>My description of a monk did not mean to portray them as a completely lousy class, just not so useful in the 50s stage. You refer to sebilis alot in your post, and I chose that as my hunting grounds throughout my 50s career so i will respond on that. In ANY sebilis pickup group, when a puller is to be chosen, the higher level melee always assumes that position. Thats just how it is. When I was level 59, and we would pick up a 60 warrior/SK/pally/ranger/bard, they would always be chosen as the puller, completely ignoring the fact i am a monk. Same would go for other levels. I agree that us monks have the innate ability to stop adds, but unfortantley that doesnt work to well in sebilis with the enormous amounts of casters. Sure, feigning off 2 casters is cake, but 4 and up becomes hairy, where luck is required. As for our ability to tank? With cleric buffs, and shaman slow I can make a great tank for the group, the problem is if you have no HP buffs on (probably unlikely but follow my example) and the frog is hasted (very frequent) your HP will drop very fast. Even with cleric buffs without a slow on the mob, and especially if the mob is hasted, your HP really doesnt stay up there too quick (ask any cleric). It becomes harder when you do harder camps like king and get aggro on those myconid warriors which you have to FD to let warrior regain aggro or you will drain the cleric's mana. <br><br>I said mages outdamage monks simply because i believe they do... a mage using his air pet does a heck of alot of damage, combined with the powerful nukes thrown in here and there (Didn't say the pet outdamages the monk alone). <br><br>But as I said earlier.. Monks are sort of like a hybrid melee at this stage.. not the tanking capability of a warrior, not the damaging capability of a rogue.. and most groups would rather have one or the other.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
